{
  "id": "fa-u1-l1",
  "unitId": "fa-u1",
  "title": "Factor by Tiles",
  "description": "Drag factor tiles into both slots to match the expression.",
  "estimatedMinutes": 20,
  "phase": "M2",
  "rounds": [
    {
      "id": "fa-u1-l1-r1",
      "label": "Warm-up",
      "problemIds": ["fa-u1-l1-r1-p1", "fa-u1-l1-r1-p2", "fa-u1-l1-r1-p3", "fa-u1-l1-r1-p4", "fa-u1-l1-r1-p5"],
      "miniLesson": {
        "title": "Factoring Trinomials",
        "paragraph": "To factor $x^2 + bx + c$, find two numbers that **multiply** to $c$ and **add** to $b$. Those two numbers become the constants inside $(x + \\_)(x + \\_)$. When both $b$ and $c$ are positive, both numbers are positive too.",
        "example": {
          "prompt": "Drag the correct factors of $x^2 + 4x + 3$ into both slots.",
          "visual": { "kind": "factoring-expression", "props": { "expression": "x^2 + 4x + 3" } },
          "interaction": {
            "type": "factoring",
            "data": {
              "draggables": [
                { "id": "a", "label": "$(x+1)$" },
                { "id": "b", "label": "$(x+3)$" },
                { "id": "c", "label": "$(x+2)$" }
              ],
              "dropZones": [
                { "id": "left", "label": "First factor" },
                { "id": "right", "label": "Second factor" }
              ],
              "correctPlacement": { "left": "a", "right": "b" },
              "acceptCommutative": true
            }
          },
          "explanation": "$x^2 + 4x + 3 = (x+1)(x+3)$ because $1 \\times 3 = 3$ and $1 + 3 = 4$."
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "fa-u1-l1-r2",
      "label": "Basics",
      "problemIds": ["fa-u1-l1-r2-p1", "fa-u1-l1-r2-p2", "fa-u1-l1-r2-p3", "fa-u1-l1-r2-p4", "fa-u1-l1-r2-p5"],
      "miniLesson": {
        "title": "Watching the Signs",
        "paragraph": "The same multiply-and-add trick still works, but now the signs matter. A **positive** constant with a negative middle term means both numbers are negative. A **negative** constant means one number is positive and one is negative, with the larger number carrying the sign of the middle term.",
        "example": {
          "prompt": "Drag the correct factors of $x^2 - 3x + 2$ into both slots.",
          "visual": { "kind": "factoring-expression", "props": { "expression": "x^2 - 3x + 2" } },
          "interaction": {
            "type": "factoring",
            "data": {
              "draggables": [
                { "id": "a", "label": "$(x-1)$" },
                { "id": "b", "label": "$(x-2)$" },
                { "id": "c", "label": "$(x+1)$" },
                { "id": "d", "label": "$(x+2)$" }
              ],
              "dropZones": [
                { "id": "left", "label": "First factor" },
                { "id": "right", "label": "Second factor" }
              ],
              "correctPlacement": { "left": "a", "right": "b" },
              "acceptCommutative": true
            }
          },
          "explanation": "$x^2 - 3x + 2 = (x-1)(x-2)$ because $(-1) \\times (-2) = 2$ and $(-1) + (-2) = -3$."
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "fa-u1-l1-r3",
      "label": "Building",
      "problemIds": ["fa-u1-l1-r3-p1", "fa-u1-l1-r3-p2", "fa-u1-l1-r3-p3", "fa-u1-l1-r3-p4", "fa-u1-l1-r3-p5"],
      "miniLesson": {
        "title": "Difference of Squares",
        "paragraph": "An expression like $x^2 - c$ with **no middle term** and a perfect-square constant is a **difference of squares**. It factors as $(x + \\sqrt{c})(x - \\sqrt{c})$ — one plus and one minus. The matching $+$ and $-$ cancel the middle term when multiplied out.",
        "example": {
          "prompt": "Drag the correct factors of $x^2 - 4$ into both slots.",
          "visual": { "kind": "factoring-expression", "props": { "expression": "x^2 - 4" } },
          "interaction": {
            "type": "factoring",
            "data": {
              "draggables": [
                { "id": "a", "label": "$(x+2)$" },
                { "id": "b", "label": "$(x-2)$" },
                { "id": "c", "label": "$(x+4)$" },
                { "id": "d", "label": "$(x-4)$" }
              ],
              "dropZones": [
                { "id": "left", "label": "First factor" },
                { "id": "right", "label": "Second factor" }
              ],
              "correctPlacement": { "left": "a", "right": "b" },
              "acceptCommutative": true
            }
          },
          "explanation": "$x^2 - 4 = (x+2)(x-2)$ — a difference of squares, since $4 = 2^2$."
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "fa-u1-l1-r4",
      "label": "Challenge",
      "problemIds": ["fa-u1-l1-r4-p1", "fa-u1-l1-r4-p2", "fa-u1-l1-r4-p3", "fa-u1-l1-r4-p4", "fa-u1-l1-r4-p5"],
      "miniLesson": {
        "title": "Bigger Numbers",
        "paragraph": "With larger constants there are more factor pairs to test, so list the pairs of $c$ and check which one **adds** to $b$. Stay alert: the round mixes trinomials and difference-of-squares, so first decide which pattern applies before you start dragging.",
        "example": {
          "prompt": "Drag the correct factors of $x^2 + 9x + 18$ into both slots.",
          "visual": { "kind": "factoring-expression", "props": { "expression": "x^2 + 9x + 18" } },
          "interaction": {
            "type": "factoring",
            "data": {
              "draggables": [
                { "id": "a", "label": "$(x+3)$" },
                { "id": "b", "label": "$(x+6)$" },
                { "id": "c", "label": "$(x+2)$" },
                { "id": "d", "label": "$(x+9)$" }
              ],
              "dropZones": [
                { "id": "left", "label": "First factor" },
                { "id": "right", "label": "Second factor" }
              ],
              "correctPlacement": { "left": "a", "right": "b" },
              "acceptCommutative": true
            }
          },
          "explanation": "$x^2 + 9x + 18 = (x+3)(x+6)$ because $3 \\times 6 = 18$ and $3 + 6 = 9$."
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "fa-u1-l1-r5",
      "label": "Mastery",
      "problemIds": ["fa-u1-l1-r5-p1", "fa-u1-l1-r5-p2", "fa-u1-l1-r5-p3", "fa-u1-l1-r5-p4", "fa-u1-l1-r5-p5"],
      "miniLesson": {
        "title": "Putting It Together",
        "paragraph": "This round blends everything: positive trinomials, sign-mixed trinomials, and difference of squares. For each problem, **identify the pattern first** — is there a middle term? what are the signs of $b$ and $c$? — then apply multiply-and-add or the difference-of-squares rule.",
        "example": {
          "prompt": "Drag the correct factors of $x^2 + 6x + 8$ into both slots.",
          "visual": { "kind": "factoring-expression", "props": { "expression": "x^2 + 6x + 8" } },
          "interaction": {
            "type": "factoring",
            "data": {
              "draggables": [
                { "id": "a", "label": "$(x+2)$" },
                { "id": "b", "label": "$(x+4)$" },
                { "id": "c", "label": "$(x+1)$" },
                { "id": "d", "label": "$(x+8)$" }
              ],
              "dropZones": [
                { "id": "left", "label": "First factor" },
                { "id": "right", "label": "Second factor" }
              ],
              "correctPlacement": { "left": "a", "right": "b" },
              "acceptCommutative": true
            }
          },
          "explanation": "$x^2 + 6x + 8 = (x+2)(x+4)$ because $2 \\times 4 = 8$ and $2 + 4 = 6$."
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}
